This notebook goes with Lesson 5, Section 14 of the Tensorflow 2.0 course on Udacity.¶

This notebook will also create a model that can recognize cats and dogs, but it will use image augmentation (and maybe neuron dropout) to make the model more robust to unforeseen images.¶

Import the required packages¶

In [2]:

Load the data¶

In [3]:

The data folders have the following structure:

cats_and_dogs_filtered
|__ train
    |______ cats: [cat.0.jpg, cat.1.jpg, cat.2.jpg ....]
    |______ dogs: [dog.0.jpg, dog.1.jpg, dog.2.jpg ...]
|__ validation
    |______ cats: [cat.2000.jpg, cat.2001.jpg, cat.2002.jpg ....]
    |______ dogs: [dog.2000.jpg, dog.2001.jpg, dog.2002.jpg ...]

Preset Model Parameters¶

BATCH_SIZE = 100
IMG_SHAPE = 150

Data Augmentation¶

We only have 2000 training images, 1000 cats and 1000 dogs. This almost surely does not encompass all possible sizes and angles and colors, etc., that pictures of dogs and cats could have. Thus, we will augment the photos we do have in order to artificially inflate the sample size. Augmentations may include rotating the images, flipping them, zooming in or out, and so on.

Let's check out some augmented pictures.

In [11]:
def plotImages(images_arr):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 5, figsize=(20,20))
    axes = axes.flatten()
    for img, ax in zip(images_arr, axes):
        ax.imshow(img)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

All Augmentations!¶

In [20]:
image_gen_train = ImageDataGenerator(rescale=1./255,
                                    rotation_range=40,
                                    width_shift_range=0.2,
                                    height_shift_range=0.2,
                                    shear_range=0.2,
                                    zoom_range=0.2,
                                    horizontal_flip=True,
                                    fill_mode='nearest')

train_data_gen = image_gen_train.flow_from_directory(batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
                                                    directory=train_dir,
                                                    shuffle=True,
                                                    target_size=(IMG_SHAPE,IMG_SHAPE),
                                                    class_mode='binary')

Found 2000 images belonging to 2 classes.

Validation Data Generator¶

val_data_gen = image_gen_val.flow_from_directory(batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
                                                directory=validation_dir,
                                                target_size=(IMG_SHAPE,IMG_SHAPE),
                                                class_mode='binary')

Found 1000 images belonging to 2 classes.

Create the model¶

We are going to use a Convolutional Neural Network on this augmented data. It will look similar to the last CNN; Four pairs of Conv2D & MaxPooling2D layers, then a Dropout layer, then Flatten, then a Dense Relu layer and then the final Dense layer.

In [23]:
model = tf.keras.models.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3,3), activation='relu', input_shape=(150, 150, 3)),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2, 2),
    
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3,3), activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(2,2),
    
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(2)
])

Compile the model¶

In [24]:
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', 
             loss = tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True),
             metrics=['accuracy'])

Train the Model¶

In [27]:
epochs = 100
history = model.fit_generator(train_data_gen,
                             steps_per_epoch=int(np.ceil(total_train / float(BATCH_SIZE))),
                             epochs = epochs,
                             validation_data = val_data_gen,
                             validation_steps = int(np.ceil(total_val / float(BATCH_SIZE))))

acc = history.history['accuracy']
val_acc = history.history['val_accuracy']

loss = history.history['loss']
val_loss = history.history['val_loss']

epochs_range = range(epochs)

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(epochs_range, acc, label='Training Accuracy')
plt.plot(epochs_range, val_acc, label='Validation Accuracy')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Accuracy')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(epochs_range, loss, label='Training Loss')
plt.plot(epochs_range, val_loss, label='Validation Loss')
plt.legend(loc='upper right')
plt.title('Training and Validation Loss')

plt.show()
